            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this Oregon local income tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Oregon does not have city income taxes in most of the state, but
                the Portland metro area has two major local income taxes on top
                of Oregon state income tax:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Metro Supportive Housing Services (SHS) tax</strong> –
                  a regional tax administered by Metro.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Multnomah County Preschool for All (PFA) tax</strong>
                  – a county‑level tax on high‑income taxpayers.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator lets you enter your income and residency
                situation and then estimates how much you might owe for each of
                these local taxes. It is designed for quick planning and
                education, not for filing a return.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Inputs</h3>
              <p>The tool uses the following inputs:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Filing status</strong> – Single/Head of Household vs.
                  Married Filing Jointly. Thresholds are higher for joint
                  filers.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Metro SHS applicability</strong> – whether you are a
                  Metro resident, a non‑resident with Metro‑sourced income, or
                  not subject to the tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Multnomah PFA applicability</strong> – whether you are
                  a Multnomah County resident, a non‑resident with
                  county‑sourced income, or not subject to the tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Wage &amp; salary income</strong> – employment income
                  subject to local tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Net self‑employment / business income</strong> – net
                  income from self‑employment and pass‑through businesses.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Adjustments / deductions</strong> – optional amount to
                  reduce the base used for local tax (for example, certain
                  losses or adjustments).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Non‑resident sourced percentage</strong> – if you are
                  a non‑resident, the share of your income that is sourced to
                  Metro or Multnomah.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Local taxable income</h3>
              <p>
                First, the calculator combines your wage and self‑employment
                income and subtracts any adjustments you enter:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Local taxable income</strong> = max( 0, (Wages +
                  Self‑employment income − Adjustments) )
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                If you select a non‑resident option, the calculator multiplies
                this amount by your <strong>sourced percentage</strong> to
                approximate the portion of income subject to Metro or Multnomah
                tax.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Modeled Metro SHS and Multnomah PFA brackets</h3>
              <p>
                The exact brackets and rates can change over time and may differ
                for different years. To keep the tool simple and transparent, we
                use <strong>illustrative progressive brackets</strong> that
                roughly mirror recent structures:
              </p>

              <h4>Metro SHS – example structure</h4>
              <p>For illustration, the calculator uses:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Single</strong>: 1% on income over $125,000; 3% on
                  income over $250,000.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Married filing jointly</strong>: 1% on income over
                  $200,000; 3% on income over $400,000.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>Below those thresholds, Metro SHS tax is treated as $0.</p>

              <h4>Multnomah PFA – example structure</h4>
              <p>For illustration, the calculator uses:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Single</strong>: 1.5% on income over $125,000; 3% on
                  income over $250,000.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Married filing jointly</strong>: 1.5% on income over
                  $200,000; 3% on income over $400,000.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Again, income below the thresholds is treated as not subject to
                PFA tax.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Progressive tax calculation (generic)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  For each bracket <em>i</em> with rate \( r_i \) and income
                  range \([L_i, U_i)\):
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Tax}_i = r_i \times \max\big(0,\ \min(\text{Taxable
                  income}, U_i) - L_i\big) \)
                </p>
                <p>Total tax is the sum of all bracket taxes.</p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Combined effective and marginal local rates</h3>
              <p>The calculator reports:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total local tax</strong> = Metro SHS tax + Multnomah
                  PFA tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Effective local rate</strong> = Total local tax ÷
                  Local taxable income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Top marginal local rate</strong> – the highest bracket
                  rate that applies to your income, combining Metro and
                  Multnomah where both apply.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Important limitations and disclaimers</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This is an <strong>educational estimator</strong>, not an
                  official calculator.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does <strong>not</strong> compute Oregon state income tax
                  or federal tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does not handle all special cases: part‑year residency,
                  complex sourcing rules, detailed business allocations,
                  credits, or exemptions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Rates and thresholds are simplified and may not match the
                  current year exactly.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>For official guidance, always refer to:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <a
                    href="https://www.oregon.gov/dor/programs/individuals/pages/pit.aspx"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    >Oregon Department of Revenue – Personal Income Tax</a
                  >
                </li>
                <li>
                  <a
                    href="https://www.portland.gov/revenue/personal-tax"
                    target="_blank"
